This reduction in hydrogen bonding ability should significantly lower the melting point. However, the remaining carboxylic acid group still allows for some hydrogen bonding, which prevents the compound from becoming a low melting liquid. The ethyl group adds some steric bulk and may also reduce the overall symmetry and planarity, which compromises efficient packing, but this effect is relatively modest.
Prediction: If isophthalic acid has a melting point of 348°C and esterification of one carboxyl group lowers the melting point by approximately -150 to -200°C, the expected melting point of isophthalic acid, monoethyl ester should be in the range of 148 to 198°C. Given that the actual value is 109.0°C, the estimate should be adjusted to account for the combined effects of reduced hydrogen bonding and steric hindrance by the ethyl group, as well as any additional conformational factors that might further decrease the melting point. The effect of the ethyl group may account for an additional decrease of -20 to -30°C. Therefore, the adjusted prediction for the melting point of isophthalic acid, monoethyl ester would be in the range of 118 to 178°C.
